    "year": "1875",
    "story": "The Western Union Telegraph Building was a building at Dey Street and Broadway in the Financial District of Manhattan in New York City. The ten-story, 230-foot-tall (70 m) structure was originally designed by George B. Post, with alterations by Henry Janeway Hardenbergh. It is considered one of the first skyscrapers in New York City. Western Union decided to construct the building in 1872 after outgrowing a previous space at 145 Broadway. Post was selected as the winner of an architectural design competition, and the building was completed in February 1875. At the time of its completion, it was one of the tallest structures in New York City, behind only Trinity Church, the New York Tribune Building, and the Brooklyn Bridge towers.",
