    "id": "w_Q2899155",
    "category": "architecture",
    "lat": 40.715139,
    "lng": -74.016528,
    "title": "Irish Hunger Memorial",
    "year": "2002",
    "story": "The Irish Hunger Memorial (Irish: Cuimhneachán Ghorta Mhóir na hÉireann) is a 0.5-acre (0.20 ha) park at the corner of Vesey Street and North End Avenue in the Battery Park City neighborhood of Manhattan in New York City. The memorial is dedicated to raising awareness of the Great Irish Hunger, referred to as An Gorta Mór in Irish, in which over one million starved to death between 1845 and 1852. In the decade after 1845, over 900,000 Irish emigrants entered the port of New York so that by 1855 Irish-born New Yorkers composed almost one third of the city's population.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Hunger_Memorial"
