    "title": "Muscota Marsh",
    "year": null,
    "story": "Muscota Marsh is a one-acre public park in the Inwood section of the borough of Manhattan in New York City, on the shore of Spuyten Duyvil Creek, a section of the Harlem River. It is adjacent to the much larger Inwood Hill Park and Columbia University's Baker Athletics Complex. The park is notable for its views and for its ecological conservation features. \"Muscota\" comes from a Lenape word meaning \"place of rushes\" or \"place in the reeds\". Before its restoration, the area was known as Boat House Marsh. Muscota Marsh is unusual for having both a freshwater marsh and a salt marsh in such a tiny area.",
